BatchDeleteRecipeVersion.name: BatchDeleteRecipeVersion
BatchDeleteRecipeVersion.documentation: Deletes one or more versions of a recipe at a time.

CreateDataset.name: CreateDataset
CreateDataset.documentation: Creates a new AWS Glue DataBrew dataset for this AWS account.

CreateProfileJob.name: CreateProfileJob
CreateProfileJob.documentation: Creates a new job to profile an AWS Glue DataBrew dataset that exists in the current AWS account.

CreateProject.name: CreateProject
CreateProject.documentation: Creates a new AWS Glue DataBrew project in the current AWS account.

CreateRecipe.name: CreateRecipe
CreateRecipe.documentation: Creates a new AWS Glue DataBrew recipe for the current AWS account.

CreateRecipeJob.name: CreateRecipeJob
CreateRecipeJob.documentation: Creates a new job for an existing AWS Glue DataBrew recipe in the current AWS account. You can create a standalone job using either a project, or a combination of a recipe and a dataset.

CreateSchedule.name: CreateSchedule
CreateSchedule.documentation: Creates a new schedule for one or more AWS Glue DataBrew jobs. Jobs can be run at a specific date and time, or at regular intervals.

DeleteDataset.name: DeleteDataset
DeleteDataset.documentation: Deletes a dataset from AWS Glue DataBrew.

DeleteJob.name: DeleteJob
DeleteJob.documentation: Deletes the specified AWS Glue DataBrew job from the current AWS account. The job can be for a recipe or for a profile.

DeleteProject.name: DeleteProject
DeleteProject.documentation: Deletes an existing AWS Glue DataBrew project from the current AWS account.

DeleteRecipeVersion.name: DeleteRecipeVersion
DeleteRecipeVersion.documentation: Deletes a single version of an AWS Glue DataBrew recipe.

DeleteSchedule.name: DeleteSchedule
DeleteSchedule.documentation: Deletes the specified AWS Glue DataBrew schedule from the current AWS account.

DescribeDataset.name: DescribeDataset
DescribeDataset.documentation: Returns the definition of a specific AWS Glue DataBrew dataset that is in the current AWS account.

DescribeJob.name: DescribeJob
DescribeJob.documentation: Returns the definition of a specific AWS Glue DataBrew job that is in the current AWS account.

DescribeProject.name: DescribeProject
DescribeProject.documentation: Returns the definition of a specific AWS Glue DataBrew project that is in the current AWS account.

DescribeRecipe.name: DescribeRecipe
DescribeRecipe.documentation: Returns the definition of a specific AWS Glue DataBrew recipe that is in the current AWS account.

DescribeSchedule.name: DescribeSchedule
DescribeSchedule.documentation: Returns the definition of a specific AWS Glue DataBrew schedule that is in the current AWS account.

ListDatasets.name: ListDatasets
ListDatasets.documentation: Lists all of the AWS Glue DataBrew datasets for the current AWS account.

ListJobRuns.name: ListJobRuns
ListJobRuns.documentation: Lists all of the previous runs of a particular AWS Glue DataBrew job in the current AWS account.

ListJobs.name: ListJobs
ListJobs.documentation: Lists the AWS Glue DataBrew jobs in the current AWS account.

ListProjects.name: ListProjects
ListProjects.documentation: Lists all of the DataBrew projects in the current AWS account.

ListRecipeVersions.name: ListRecipeVersions
ListRecipeVersions.documentation: Lists all of the versions of a particular AWS Glue DataBrew recipe in the current AWS account.

ListRecipes.name: ListRecipes
ListRecipes.documentation: Lists all of the AWS Glue DataBrew recipes in the current AWS account.

ListSchedules.name: ListSchedules
ListSchedules.documentation: Lists the AWS Glue DataBrew schedules in the current AWS account.

ListTagsForResource.name: ListTagsForResource
ListTagsForResource.documentation: Lists all the tags for an AWS Glue DataBrew resource.

PublishRecipe.name: PublishRecipe
PublishRecipe.documentation: Publishes a new major version of an AWS Glue DataBrew recipe that exists in the current AWS account.

SendProjectSessionAction.name: SendProjectSessionAction
SendProjectSessionAction.documentation: Performs a recipe step within an interactive AWS Glue DataBrew session that's currently open.

StartJobRun.name: StartJobRun
StartJobRun.documentation: Runs an AWS Glue DataBrew job that exists in the current AWS account.

StartProjectSession.name: StartProjectSession
StartProjectSession.documentation: Creates an interactive session, enabling you to manipulate an AWS Glue DataBrew project.

StopJobRun.name: StopJobRun
StopJobRun.documentation: Stops the specified job from running in the current AWS account.

TagResource.name: TagResource
TagResource.documentation: Adds metadata tags to an AWS Glue DataBrew resource, such as a dataset, job, project, or recipe.

UntagResource.name: UntagResource
UntagResource.documentation: Removes metadata tags from an AWS Glue DataBrew resource.

UpdateDataset.name: UpdateDataset
UpdateDataset.documentation: Modifies the definition of an existing AWS Glue DataBrew dataset in the current AWS account.

UpdateProfileJob.name: UpdateProfileJob
UpdateProfileJob.documentation: Modifies the definition of an existing AWS Glue DataBrew job in the current AWS account.

UpdateProject.name: UpdateProject
UpdateProject.documentation: Modifies the definition of an existing AWS Glue DataBrew project in the current AWS account.

UpdateRecipe.name: UpdateRecipe
UpdateRecipe.documentation: Modifies the definition of the latest working version of an AWS Glue DataBrew recipe in the current AWS account.

UpdateRecipeJob.name: UpdateRecipeJob
UpdateRecipeJob.documentation: Modifies the definition of an existing AWS Glue DataBrew recipe job in the current AWS account.

UpdateSchedule.name: UpdateSchedule
UpdateSchedule.documentation: Modifies the definition of an existing AWS Glue DataBrew schedule in the current AWS account.

Condition.documentation: A specific condition to apply to a recipe action. For more information, see Recipe structure in the AWS Glue DataBrew Developer Guide.

Value.documentation: A value that the condition must evaluate to for the condition to succeed.

TargetColumn.documentation: A column to apply this condition to, within an AWS Glue DataBrew dataset.

ConditionExpression.documentation:
Represents an individual condition that evaluates to true or false.

Conditions are used with recipe actions: The action is only performed for column values where the condition evaluates to true.

If a recipe requires more than one condition, then the recipe must specify multiple ConditionExpression elements. Each condition is applied to the rows in a dataset first, before the recipe action is performed.

ConflictException.documentation: Updating or deleting a resource can cause an inconsistent state.

ClientSessionId.documentation: A unique identifier for an interactive session that's currently open and ready for work. The action will be performed on this session.

Result.documentation: A message indicating the result of performing the action.

Name.documentation: The name of the project that was affected by the action.

ActionId.documentation: A unique identifier for the action that was performed.

Name.documentation: The name of the job to be run.

RunId.documentation: A system-generated identifier for this particular job run.

Name.documentation: The name of the project to act upon.

AssumeControl.documentation: A value that, if true, enables you to take control of a session, even if a different client is currently accessing the project.

Name.documentation: The name of the project to be acted upon.
The name of the job to be stopped.

RunId.documentation: The ID of the job run to be stopped.
The ID of the job run that you stopped.

ResourceArn.documentation: The DataBrew resource to which tags should be added. The value for this parameter is an Amazon Resource Name (ARN). For DataBrew, you can tag a dataset, a job, a project, or a recipe.

Tags.documentation: One or more tags to be assigned to the resource.

ResourceArn.documentation: An DataBrew resource from which you want to remove a tag or tags. The value for this parameter is an Amazon Resource Name (ARN).

TagKeys.documentation: The tag keys (names) of one or more tags to be removed.

Name.documentation: The name of the dataset to be updated.
The name of the dataset that you updated.

EncryptionKeyArn.documentation: The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of an encryption key that is used to protect the job.

EncryptionMode.documentation:
The encryption mode for the job, which can be one of the following:

  • SSE-KMS - Server-side encryption with AWS KMS-managed keys.

  • SSE-S3 - Server-side encryption with keys managed by Amazon S3.

Name.documentation: The name of the job to be updated.

LogSubscription.documentation: A value that enables or disables Amazon CloudWatch logging for the current AWS account. If logging is enabled, CloudWatch writes one log stream for each job run.

MaxCapacity.documentation: The maximum number of nodes that DataBrew can use when the job processes data.

MaxRetries.documentation: The maximum number of times to retry the job after a job run fails.

RoleArn.documentation: The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the AWS Identity and Access Management (IAM) role to be assumed for this request.

Timeout.documentation: The job's timeout in minutes. A job that attempts to run longer than this timeout period ends with a status of TIMEOUT.

Name.documentation: The name of the job that was updated.

RoleArn.documentation: The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the IAM role to be assumed for this request.

Name.documentation: The name of the project to be updated.

LastModifiedDate.documentation: The date and time that the project was last modified.

Name.documentation: The name of the project that you updated.

EncryptionKeyArn.documentation: The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of an encryption key that is used to protect the job.

EncryptionMode.documentation:
The encryption mode for the job, which can be one of the following:

  • SSE-KMS - Server-side encryption with AWS KMS-managed keys.

  • SSE-S3 - Server-side encryption with keys managed by Amazon S3.

Name.documentation: The name of the job to update.

LogSubscription.documentation: A value that enables or disables Amazon CloudWatch logging for the current AWS account. If logging is enabled, CloudWatch writes one log stream for each job run.

MaxCapacity.documentation: The maximum number of nodes that DataBrew can consume when the job processes data.

MaxRetries.documentation: The maximum number of times to retry the job after a job run fails.

Outputs.documentation: One or more artifacts that represent the output from running the job.

RoleArn.documentation: The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the AWS Identity and Access Management (IAM) role to be assumed for this request.

Timeout.documentation: The job's timeout in minutes. A job that attempts to run longer than this timeout period ends with a status of TIMEOUT.

Name.documentation: The name of the job that you updated.
The name of the recipe to be updated.

Steps.documentation: One or more steps to be performed by the recipe. Each step consists of an action, and the conditions under which the action should succeed.

Name.documentation: The name of the recipe that was updated.

JobNames.documentation: The name or names of one or more jobs to be run for this schedule.

CronExpression.documentation: The date or dates and time or times, in cron format, when the jobs are to be run.

Name.documentation: The name of the schedule to update.
The name of the schedule that was updated.

ValidationException.documentation: The input parameters for this request failed validation.

StartColumnIndex.documentation: The starting index for the range of columns to return in the view frame.

ColumnRange.documentation: The number of columns to include in the view frame, beginning with the StartColumnIndex value and ignoring any columns in the HiddenColumns list.

HiddenColumns.documentation: A list of columns to hide in the view frame.

ViewFrame.documentation: Represents the data being being transformed during an AWS Glue DataBrew project session.

documentation: AWS Glue DataBrew is a visual, cloud-scale data-preparation service. DataBrew simplifies data preparation tasks, targeting data issues that are hard to spot and time-consuming to fix. DataBrew empowers users of all technical levels to visualize the data and perform one-click data transformations, with no coding required.
